title: Grateful Dead Live at The Centrum on 1988-04-08

Stagger Lee

Loser  ->

Set 2

Drums  ->

The Other One  ->

reviews.review_text: 4-8-88 A strong performance and another fine sounding remaster by C Miller.

Great example of that rubbery April '88 sound This middle night of the Worcester run clocks in at only 2 hours. It’s compact timewise, but pretty loose sonically. Jerry’s voice is a bit hoarse, but it’s not nearly as bad as it is in the Hartford shows. The middle of the first set features three exceptional Garcia guitar solos, each with a different tone and flavor. He shreds his Rooster solo to ribbons, offers a brighter, more compassionate, but equally impressive solo during Queen Jane, and then switches on the flamethrower to blaze into the peak of perhaps the greatest (certainly the most underrated) Loser of all time. The song just absolutely explodes.

The second set is a classic selection of old favorites, all performed pretty quickly. Playin’ and The Other One, both known to often span 10-15 minutes in the 80’s, barely crack 6 minutes apiece. The first couple jam vehicles, Playin’ and Crazy Fingers, both segue out into the next song just as they really get cooking. What’s the rush boys? Uncle John’s Band is hearty and patriotic. What better place than Massachusetts to sing about walls of cannonballs and the DON’T TREAD ON ME motto. Post-Space, we get a pretty grim Black Peter. Black Muddy River starts off as a cautious stroll through a fairly new song, and soon strengthens into a soulful and impressive rendition.

It’s fun to zip through one of these bouncy Spring ‘88 soundboards every now and then. This has to be one of the shortest complete shows of the era. The meat of the first set is probably the highlight, but be sure to check out that speedy second set too!
